WEBVTT

00:06.000 --> 00:12.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:44.600 --> 00:45.740
[GIRL GIGGLES]

00:45.840 --> 00:47.405
It's squishy!

00:49.840 --> 00:52.220
There's little fish, Troy! Come see!

00:52.320 --> 00:53.567
TROY: Mandy!

00:53.880 --> 00:56.367
Mandy, come back! Mom's gonna be mad!

01:01.800 --> 01:04.810
[WHISTLING NEARBY]

01:10.000 --> 01:11.565
Mandy!

01:14.880 --> 01:17.208
[DOLPHIN SQUEALING]

01:44.320 --> 01:47.500
<i>SAWYER: When CMA staff and
volunteers arrived on scene...</i>

01:47.600 --> 01:52.300
<i>CMA 1307A was found on
her left side struggling.</i>

01:52.400 --> 01:53.540
MAN 1: Right behind you.

01:53.640 --> 01:55.500
<i>SAWYER:
Her blowhole was largely underwater.</i>

01:55.600 --> 01:57.325
WOMAN: Okay, don't stress it.

01:57.840 --> 01:59.180
Bring in the stretcher!

01:59.280 --> 02:01.860
<i>SAWYER: She had small lesions,
mucus coming out of her eyes...</i>

02:01.960 --> 02:03.740
<i>and was severely sunburned.</i>

02:03.840 --> 02:05.740
<i>A common problem with
beached dolphins...</i>

02:05.840 --> 02:09.646
<i>as their skin isn't adapted for
prolonged exposure to the sun.</i>

02:10.080 --> 02:14.922
<i>The team suspected possible lung infection,
which led to her being disoriented...</i>

02:15.320 --> 02:17.260
<i>which led to her beaching.</i>

02:17.360 --> 02:21.460
<i>This dolphin was nicknamed Mandy,
after the little girl who discovered her.</i>

02:21.560 --> 02:23.220
It's 92. It's really, really high.

02:23.320 --> 02:26.220
<i>SAWYER: Now, science doesn't know
whether dolphins feel emotions...</i>

02:26.320 --> 02:30.809
<i>the way we do: fear, joy, sadness.</i>

02:31.040 --> 02:33.140
<i>But their brains are
as complex as ours...</i>

02:33.240 --> 02:35.647
<i>and to us, Mandy seemed terrified.</i>

02:36.960 --> 02:41.324
<i>So, like always, we treated her
as gently as we treat one of us.</i>

02:41.480 --> 02:44.540
<i>We managed to get her into a stretcher
and over to the rescue vehicle...</i>

02:44.640 --> 02:45.780
PHOEBE: Breath!

02:45.880 --> 02:49.050
<i>SAWYER: ...which wasn't easy,
as the area was a mud flat.</i>

02:49.960 --> 02:51.900
- Phoebe, you all right?
- Watch your step.

02:52.000 --> 02:56.260
<i>SAWYER: Mandy was eight and a half feet
long and weighed approximately 350 pounds.</i>

02:56.360 --> 02:57.925
PHOEBE: Breath.

02:58.800 --> 03:01.082
- MAN 2: Watch your step.
- PHOEBE: Thanks, Kyle.

03:02.720 --> 03:05.700
<i>SAWYER: When we got her back to CMA,
we immediately began giving her...</i>

03:05.800 --> 03:09.402
<i>fluids and antibiotics for
her respiratory infection...</i>

03:10.960 --> 03:13.162
<i>as well as a topical
ointment for her sunburn.</i>

03:15.080 --> 03:17.500
Since then, she's been gaining
strength every day...

03:17.600 --> 03:21.060
and is well on the road back
to being a healthy animal.

03:21.160 --> 03:23.931
[ALL CLAPPING]

03:27.000 --> 03:30.727
All right. Next session, we'll go
into more details about strandings.

03:31.920 --> 03:33.940
I just want to thank
you for volunteering.

03:34.040 --> 03:36.140
You guys are what keep
this aquarium going.

03:36.240 --> 03:38.740
You and really big
truckloads of fish.

03:38.840 --> 03:40.020
[ALL CHUCKLE]

03:40.120 --> 03:41.890
See you Wednesday!

03:44.920 --> 03:46.360
Hi. Excuse me?

03:47.240 --> 03:50.300
Sorry, um, we just
wanted to say thanks.

03:50.400 --> 03:53.100
We volunteered because we
heard all about you and Winter.

03:53.200 --> 03:56.500
All Susie ever talks about is dolphins.
She wants to be just like you.

03:56.600 --> 04:00.566
- I do not!
- Sawyer! We're starting in 10 minutes.

04:01.200 --> 04:02.340
Oh.

04:02.440 --> 04:05.246
Right. Excuse me.

04:13.560 --> 04:17.446
<i>Hi. I'm Hazel Haskett, and welcome
to the Clearwater Marine Aquarium.</i>

04:17.880 --> 04:22.019
<i>Fifteen years ago, my mom and dad
bought an old sewage treatment plant...</i>

04:22.120 --> 04:25.380
<i>and turned it into a hospital for
sick and injured marine animals.</i>

04:25.480 --> 04:29.260
<i>Their goal was to rescue, rehab and
release as many animals as they could.</i>

04:29.360 --> 04:34.540
<i>Today Clearwater Marine Aquarium is home
to turtles, otters, sharks, and dolphins...</i>

04:34.640 --> 04:37.980
<i>including Winter, the famous
dolphin with the prosthetic tail.</i>

04:38.080 --> 04:40.540
<i>If you're interested in
volunteering at CMA...</i>

04:40.640 --> 04:42.780
<i>please see our staff
at Guest Services.</i>

04:42.880 --> 04:45.780
<i>Enjoy your day here at
Clearwater Marine Aquarium.</i>

04:45.880 --> 04:48.287
[PEOPLE SHRIEKING AND GASPING]

04:54.760 --> 04:56.450
[GRUNTS]

04:56.920 --> 04:59.043
[CHATTERING]

05:01.840 --> 05:03.121
[GASPS]

05:04.680 --> 05:05.961
[MOTHER SHRIEKING]

05:07.280 --> 05:08.500
MOTHER: Shoo!

05:08.600 --> 05:10.882
Hey! What the heck...?

05:11.920 --> 05:14.248
- Ah! Oh.
- My bear!

05:14.760 --> 05:16.530
Rufus, no!

05:17.240 --> 05:19.300
I'm sorry, honey. Are you okay?

05:19.400 --> 05:21.180
Ma'am, I am so sorry.

05:21.280 --> 05:24.180
If you can't control your pelican,
you really shouldn't have him here.

05:24.280 --> 05:26.580
He's not exactly our pelican.

05:26.680 --> 05:28.086
Whose pelican is he then?

05:28.640 --> 05:31.060
You know, I don't think he
really belongs to anybody.

05:31.160 --> 05:32.620
You okay?

05:32.720 --> 05:34.860
Um, look, I really would
like to make it up to you.

05:34.960 --> 05:38.180
How about if I take you down to the
gift shop? And I'll get you something new.

05:38.280 --> 05:39.891
Anything.

05:40.040 --> 05:42.220
- Is that okay, honey?
- Mm-hm.

05:42.320 --> 05:44.780
Hi, guys! Welcome to
Clearwater Marine Aquarium!

05:44.880 --> 05:46.340
How's everybody doing today?

05:46.440 --> 05:48.244
[CHEERING]

05:52.360 --> 05:56.180
Thank you. We are so excited that you
chose to spend your day with us.

05:56.280 --> 05:58.260
And today we have
a very special guest.

05:58.360 --> 06:02.780
Please give a warm welcome to
champion surfer, Bethany Hamilton!

06:02.880 --> 06:05.367
[CHEERING]

06:07.800 --> 06:11.220
Thank you, Hazel.
I am so stoked to be here.

06:11.320 --> 06:14.808
How about everyone out here?
You stoked?

06:19.200 --> 06:22.620
And being able to spend time
with Winter, who has just been...

06:22.720 --> 06:25.580
such an inspiration for me,
and I'm sure to you as well.

06:25.680 --> 06:27.370
Isn't she just amazing?

06:29.480 --> 06:30.620
[CROWD LAUGHING]

06:30.720 --> 06:32.410
So thank you!

06:35.480 --> 06:38.660
HAZEL: Winter usually does three
sessions a day with her prosthetic...

06:38.760 --> 06:40.860
and as you can see,
she really likes it.

06:40.960 --> 06:43.620
With it on, she's able to
swim normally, and already...

06:43.720 --> 06:45.900
it's helped to correct the
damage to her spine...

06:46.000 --> 06:48.220
and she's able to live
a healthy, happy life.

06:48.320 --> 06:49.460
Do you see her?

06:49.560 --> 06:51.410
PHOEBE:
Hold it out where she can see it.

06:53.640 --> 06:55.080
[CLICKING]

06:55.560 --> 06:56.921
You okay?

06:59.200 --> 07:01.482
[CROWD LAUGHS]

07:02.840 --> 07:04.260
Cut it out!

07:04.360 --> 07:05.700
Looks like Winter's being
extra playful today.

07:05.800 --> 07:07.100
She's being a brat.

07:07.200 --> 07:09.300
- Maybe it's me.
- No, no, she loves people.

07:09.400 --> 07:12.444
She's just in a weird mood,
for some reason.

07:13.560 --> 07:15.000
[WINTER WHISTLING]

07:16.560 --> 07:17.700
She's refusing.

07:17.800 --> 07:21.163
Can you gate Panama?
I think she's distracting.

07:21.560 --> 07:25.780
That's Panama. She was rescued
12 years ago, unable to catch fish.

07:25.880 --> 07:27.020
And we found out why.

07:27.120 --> 07:30.380
It's actually because she's deaf,
which makes her unable to echolocate.

07:30.480 --> 07:34.287
She's also very old for a dolphin.
Over 40, we think.

07:34.400 --> 07:36.300
Heh. I know. It's really old.

07:36.400 --> 07:39.300
Heh. But she and Winter
are the best of friends.

07:39.400 --> 07:41.090
There she goes!

07:41.400 --> 07:43.060
- Hey, Doc.
- Hey.

07:43.160 --> 07:45.300
How are you? So glad you
could make it down here.

07:45.400 --> 07:46.647
Glad to be here.

07:46.760 --> 07:48.380
BETHANY:
Good girl, Winter. Good girl.

07:48.480 --> 07:50.460
- PHOEBE: Are you ready to take her?
- SAWYER: Yup.

07:50.560 --> 07:53.127
- The two of them are just spectacular.
- Oh, yeah.

07:53.480 --> 07:54.660
- You ready?
- Mm-hm.

07:54.760 --> 07:56.371
SAWYER: Come on.

08:09.600 --> 08:12.644
[AUDIENCE CHEERING]

09:08.160 --> 09:10.140
[WINTER WHISTLING AND
BETHANY CHUCKLING]

09:10.240 --> 09:12.060
[CROWD CHEERING]

09:12.160 --> 09:13.620
BETHANY: Attagirl!

09:13.720 --> 09:15.570
[AUDIENCE CHEERING]

09:16.000 --> 09:18.362
WOMAN 1: We love you, Bethany!

09:30.480 --> 09:32.091
SAWYER: Phoebe.

09:33.480 --> 09:35.125
Thanks.

09:35.360 --> 09:36.891
Hey.

09:37.160 --> 09:38.420
How you doing?

09:38.520 --> 09:40.085
[WHISTLING]

09:41.880 --> 09:43.969
You want your mattress?

09:46.360 --> 09:48.060
Here you go.

09:48.160 --> 09:49.407
All right.

09:50.160 --> 09:51.340
[CLICKING]

09:51.440 --> 09:53.324
You don't want your mattress?

09:56.800 --> 09:58.286
Okay.

09:58.880 --> 10:00.809
Gotta go, all right?

10:02.280 --> 10:03.980
I'll see you tomorrow.

10:04.080 --> 10:06.089
[WHISTLING]

10:09.680 --> 10:12.645
Hey! Winter! What are you doing?

10:13.520 --> 10:14.900
What's wrong with her?

10:15.000 --> 10:18.329
I don't know.
She's acting really strange.

10:18.920 --> 10:21.248
[CLICKING]

10:21.720 --> 10:24.660
Panama is too. She didn't eat
her 2 p.m. bucket or her 5.

10:24.760 --> 10:26.220
You tell Clay?

10:26.320 --> 10:28.522
Yeah. He had a look at her.

10:31.320 --> 10:33.807
He's gonna run some
more tests tomorrow.

10:35.760 --> 10:39.203
[CLICKING AND SQUEALING]

11:06.680 --> 11:08.020
SAWYER: Hey, Mom.

11:08.120 --> 11:09.731
Hi, hon.

11:11.800 --> 11:13.900
I'd like you to meet someone.

11:14.000 --> 11:15.980
This is Professor Miguel Arroyo.

11:16.080 --> 11:17.700
Hi. Nice to meet you.

11:17.800 --> 11:19.968
LORRAINE: Come have a seat.

11:21.040 --> 11:22.605
SAWYER: Okay.

11:24.600 --> 11:26.620
Sawyer, I watched you
today with Winter...

11:26.720 --> 11:31.700
and everything Kyle tells me seems to
be true. You're really good with dolphins.

11:31.800 --> 11:34.900
Dr. Arroyo is my advisor
at Boston University.

11:35.000 --> 11:37.487
He's helping me get into med school.

11:37.800 --> 11:38.940
Okay.

11:39.040 --> 11:42.620
I'll get right to the point. We have a
special program at the university...

11:42.720 --> 11:45.844
for marine biology students.
It's called Sea Semester.

11:46.120 --> 11:50.300
Twelve weeks on a sailing ship. Full
learning experience right on the ocean.

11:50.400 --> 11:53.500
This semester we're
emphasizing marine mammals.

11:53.600 --> 11:55.900
Our students get hands-on teaching...

11:56.000 --> 11:59.249
from some of the finest
scientific minds in the country.

11:59.440 --> 12:03.008
Sailing on a tall ship,
cruising through the Caribbean...

12:03.520 --> 12:07.486
and watching wild dolphins in some of
the most beautiful waters on Earth.

12:08.120 --> 12:11.767
Every year, we invite one gifted
high school student to join us...

12:12.600 --> 12:15.121
and this year we'd like
that student to be you.

12:19.720 --> 12:21.020
It's a challenge.

12:21.120 --> 12:24.460
The science is rigorous,
but I think you can handle it.

12:24.560 --> 12:27.500
And I promise you it'll be an
experience you'll never forget.

12:27.600 --> 12:31.771
And it's a full scholarship.
All paid for.

12:33.080 --> 12:34.220
What...?

12:34.320 --> 12:37.860
Full academic credit at school. All I have
to do is speak to the guidance counselor...

12:37.960 --> 12:41.940
and come Fall, if you decide you're in,
you'd fly with Kyle to Boston...

12:42.040 --> 12:43.810
And we'll take care of the rest.

12:43.960 --> 12:47.500
To be honest, your work with Winter
is very well known in our field.

12:47.600 --> 12:51.566
It would be an honor to
have you as our student.

13:19.680 --> 13:21.540
<i>MAN [OVER PA]:
The Aquarium is now closed.</i>

13:21.640 --> 13:24.660
<i>Please exit the building.
We apologize.</i>

13:24.760 --> 13:27.380
<i>The aquarium is now
closed for the day.</i>

13:27.480 --> 13:30.206
<i>We apologize for any inconvenience.</i>

13:31.240 --> 13:34.060
I'm so sorry. There's been an emergency.
That's really all I can say.

13:34.160 --> 13:37.011
- Rebecca! What's going on?
- You've gotta go talk to Clay.

13:38.200 --> 13:40.220
REBECCA: Sorry for the inconvenience.

13:40.320 --> 13:42.682
Thank you for your understanding.
I'm sorry.

13:45.640 --> 13:48.207
[WOMAN SOBBING]

13:53.240 --> 13:55.966
[SOBBING]

13:57.440 --> 13:59.085
[GASPS]

13:59.440 --> 14:01.244
Panama!

14:05.920 --> 14:07.690
What happened?

14:08.920 --> 14:10.849
We just don't know.

14:11.160 --> 14:16.002
She, uh, took one last breath
and went to the bottom.

14:19.280 --> 14:22.962
Kat was there, but there
was nothing she could do.

14:23.560 --> 14:24.740
[WINTER WHISTLING]

14:24.840 --> 14:26.201
Winter.

14:32.800 --> 14:34.740
Winter's fine.

14:34.840 --> 14:36.060
We had them separated.

14:36.160 --> 14:38.886
We needed Panama alone
to do some tests.

14:50.040 --> 14:52.083
She was just so old.

14:53.680 --> 14:55.609
Could have been anything.

15:00.080 --> 15:01.725
Yeah.

15:11.000 --> 15:12.690
[RUFUS GRUNTS]

15:31.520 --> 15:33.563
- Hey.
- Hey.

15:34.000 --> 15:36.940
Come in. Or up, or whatever.

15:37.040 --> 15:38.605
Thanks.

15:44.240 --> 15:45.771
How you doing?

15:49.920 --> 15:52.521
It's funny. I never
come up here anymore.

15:52.800 --> 15:55.526
I used to spend hours
and hours up here.

15:55.760 --> 15:57.405
[RUFUS GRUNTING]

16:00.480 --> 16:02.967
[SOBBING]
Why do these things have to happen?

16:06.560 --> 16:08.285
Wish I knew.

16:09.120 --> 16:11.163
I loved Panama.

16:11.920 --> 16:14.202
I'm gonna miss her so much.

16:14.520 --> 16:17.740
She was good, you know?
She was gentle.

16:17.840 --> 16:19.485
Yeah.

16:22.160 --> 16:26.220
If you could turn the clock
back to whenever you want...

16:26.320 --> 16:31.481
and make everything
exactly the way it used to be...

16:31.920 --> 16:33.201
would you?

16:38.120 --> 16:40.288
Maybe. But...

16:43.160 --> 16:45.249
I don't really know.

16:47.720 --> 16:49.206
Yeah.

16:55.680 --> 16:57.644
Come here, Winter.

17:02.200 --> 17:03.890
[SIGHS]

17:23.520 --> 17:25.050
How's our girl?

17:26.000 --> 17:28.406
Mostly just staying
under the platform.

17:33.960 --> 17:36.242
Think she knew Panama was dying?

17:38.160 --> 17:40.203
It's hard to say.

17:40.960 --> 17:45.449
She may have seen something
inside Panama that we couldn't.

17:46.440 --> 17:48.608
Who knows? Maybe she
was trying to tell us.

17:51.080 --> 17:55.171
It's really good that
you're keeping her company.

17:56.560 --> 17:58.330
What's that?

17:58.440 --> 18:00.100
SAWYER: Oh.

18:00.200 --> 18:01.606
Yeah, I forgot.

18:05.000 --> 18:08.220
Hey, I know this program.
It's out of Boston, right?

18:08.320 --> 18:09.851
Yeah.

18:10.720 --> 18:12.365
They invited me.

18:13.000 --> 18:17.205
That's fantastic, buddy!
That is a big deal!

18:18.560 --> 18:20.444
So when do you go?

18:21.000 --> 18:22.611
September something.

18:22.880 --> 18:28.325
But it's for three months. Think it's
okay for me to leave Winter that long?

18:28.600 --> 18:30.300
She'll be fine.

18:30.400 --> 18:32.980
SAWYER: We've gotta pair her up
with another female, don't we?

18:33.080 --> 18:34.930
CLAY: Yeah. That's true.

18:36.160 --> 18:38.124
We've got Mandy now.

18:39.200 --> 18:40.765
We do.

18:42.760 --> 18:44.405
What do they say?

18:45.400 --> 18:49.969
"Whenever one door closes,
another one opens."

18:50.080 --> 18:51.420
Yeah.

18:51.520 --> 18:54.820
[PHONE RINGS THEN RECEPTIONIST
SPEAKS INDISTINCTLY]

18:54.920 --> 18:59.180
HORDERN: So you're saying
basically she's depressed?

18:59.280 --> 19:03.980
Yeah, in dolphin terms,
yes, she's lethargic...

19:04.080 --> 19:07.740
not interacting, uh, refusing
her food for the most part.

19:07.840 --> 19:11.540
We're trying to increase
her supplements, but...

19:11.640 --> 19:13.490
What about the prosthetic?

19:13.680 --> 19:15.723
She's refusing that too.

19:16.240 --> 19:19.284
So it's possible her spine
is deteriorating again?

19:20.880 --> 19:23.048
It's possible.

19:23.760 --> 19:27.100
I have an ultrasound and x-ray
set scheduled for Friday.

19:27.200 --> 19:31.420
It's been, what, three weeks? And you've kept
her away from the public the whole time.

19:31.520 --> 19:33.940
Yup. I have.

19:34.040 --> 19:37.180
Sounds like she's missing Panama.
She's probably lonely.

19:37.280 --> 19:42.420
And isn't it against USDA regulations
to keep a dolphin in a pool alone?

19:42.520 --> 19:45.580
We have another female.
Why don't we just put Mandy in with her?

19:45.680 --> 19:48.690
I can't give you an
answer on that right now.

19:49.320 --> 19:53.060
But we're more than just a hospital now.
We're a full-blown aquarium.

19:53.160 --> 19:56.380
People are coming from all over
the world to see and learn.

19:56.480 --> 19:58.620
- I'm aware of what people...
- That allows us...

19:58.720 --> 20:02.580
to expand and build more care facilities
and pools and operating rooms.

20:02.680 --> 20:06.680
And how many of those people
have come to see Winter?

20:06.840 --> 20:08.740
[CLAY SIGHS]

20:08.840 --> 20:13.820
Clay, come on. You've seen the faces
of the kids and the veterans, right?

20:13.920 --> 20:16.740
How moved and inspired they are.

20:16.840 --> 20:18.540
Isn't that part of our mission too?

20:18.640 --> 20:21.660
You can't just throw two
dolphins in the water together!

20:21.760 --> 20:23.220
It doesn't work that way!

20:23.320 --> 20:25.860
I'm not trying to tell you
how to do your job, Clay.

20:25.960 --> 20:29.580
I'm just saying that putting Mandy
and Winter together in the pool...

20:29.680 --> 20:34.568
as soon as possible would be a heck
of a good idea. Don't you think?

20:35.040 --> 20:37.402
Come on up! Good girl.

20:38.360 --> 20:40.244
Yeah. Good girl.

20:41.280 --> 20:42.780
How's Mandy doing?

20:42.880 --> 20:44.060
SAWYER: Pretty good.

20:44.160 --> 20:45.940
Her sunburn is looking a lot better.

20:46.040 --> 20:47.810
HAZEL: Good.

20:50.200 --> 20:51.340
[GRUNTING]

20:51.440 --> 20:53.260
- What's with Rufus?
- I don't know.

20:53.360 --> 20:57.380
He's been doing that for a couple days now,
just up and down to that dock over there.

20:57.480 --> 20:58.660
Why?

20:58.760 --> 21:00.660
I don't know.
Maybe he's losing his mind.

21:00.760 --> 21:02.700
Heh. Not that there's much to lose.

21:02.800 --> 21:04.604
[SQUAWKS]

21:08.560 --> 21:10.330
Which dock is it?

21:14.880 --> 21:17.560
[GRUNTING]

21:22.920 --> 21:25.407
- What is that?
- Is there something under there?

21:31.560 --> 21:32.807
SAWYER: I don't know.

21:33.960 --> 21:35.980
- What is it?
- HAZEL: I have no idea.

21:36.080 --> 21:38.460
Oh, my gosh.

21:38.560 --> 21:40.125
[SAWYER GRUNTS]

21:44.240 --> 21:45.380
Here, get its head up!

21:45.480 --> 21:48.001
Oh, my gosh. It's all tangled.

21:48.760 --> 21:51.042
- Rufus...!
- SAWYER: We got him.

21:52.000 --> 21:54.100
[GRUNTING]

21:54.200 --> 21:55.447
Rufus...!

21:59.960 --> 22:03.084
Rufus, cut it out!
What is your issue?

22:04.880 --> 22:06.570
Go away!

22:15.800 --> 22:19.322
- Well, least she didn't swallow the hook.
- Yeah.

22:19.480 --> 22:23.082
When these guys throw their old fishing
line in the water, they just don't realize.

22:23.400 --> 22:25.523
- Ilex, please.
- Yeah.

22:26.320 --> 22:28.580
The lacerations aren't
too bad, I guess.

22:28.680 --> 22:31.340
Yeah, but we need x-rays.
Make sure nothing's broken.

22:31.440 --> 22:35.020
- CT scan?
- Yeah, and blood work. Check her glucose.

22:35.120 --> 22:38.688
- She's lost blood, her iron will be low.
- Absolutely right.

22:42.480 --> 22:44.045
[GRUNTING]

22:44.680 --> 22:48.362
- What on earth is wrong with that bird?
- Where do I start?

22:55.680 --> 22:57.006
KAT: Thanks.

22:58.000 --> 22:59.260
There she goes.

22:59.360 --> 23:00.700
All right.

23:00.800 --> 23:03.241
What do you think, guys?
What do we name her?

23:04.320 --> 23:05.885
Mavis.

23:06.320 --> 23:07.567
Mavis?

23:07.680 --> 23:11.202
- From <i>The Andy Griffith Show</i>!
- Don't you watch any TV from this century?

23:15.840 --> 23:17.690
Great. Now he's a bodyguard.

23:20.400 --> 23:22.220
<i>WOMAN [OVER PA]:
Please pardon our clutter.</i>

23:22.320 --> 23:24.460
MCCARTHY: Excuse me, look out!
Look out! Excuse me!

23:24.560 --> 23:27.500
GIRL: You can't get in without a ticket.
Do you have a ticket?

23:27.600 --> 23:29.860
No, I don't have a ticket,
nor do I intend to buy one.

23:29.960 --> 23:31.940
- You need to buy a ticket.
- Stop clawing at me!

23:32.040 --> 23:34.980
- I've got jars of peanut butter older than you.
- But, sir...

23:35.080 --> 23:37.740
Get your grubby hands
off my case, piranha!

23:37.840 --> 23:39.201
Dr. McCarthy!

23:40.480 --> 23:42.180
You can let him in. He's our guest.

23:42.280 --> 23:44.323
- Sorry, sir.
- SAWYER: All right.

23:44.720 --> 23:47.900
I'm sorry. There are so many new
people here, they didn't know who you were.

23:48.000 --> 23:49.929
That much is obvious.

23:50.360 --> 23:52.860
We have a standing appointment,
every 6 months.

23:52.960 --> 23:56.180
I'm so sorry.
It totally slipped my mind.

23:56.280 --> 23:58.460
Surely she's outgrown
the last tail by now.

23:58.560 --> 24:00.700
The trick has been trying
to get her to wear it.

24:00.800 --> 24:04.561
I'm so sorry, but no one's allowed
back here. Winter's not feeling very well.

24:05.760 --> 24:07.246
- GIRL: Why?
- I'm sorry, girls.

24:08.800 --> 24:10.047
[MCCARTHY SIGHS]

24:20.360 --> 24:24.020
- Does she ever come out?
- Not much. Not since Panama died.

24:24.120 --> 24:26.448
It's hard to even
coax her out to eat.

24:27.240 --> 24:28.726
You ever try bacon?

24:30.480 --> 24:33.180
- It works with my cat.
- Heh.

24:33.280 --> 24:35.050
SAWYER: Yep. Thanks.

24:35.840 --> 24:38.281
All right. Come on, Winter.

24:38.840 --> 24:40.485
Up you go.

24:42.560 --> 24:43.980
Don't rush her now.

24:44.080 --> 24:45.964
Nice and slow, Sawyer.

24:46.080 --> 24:48.660
There you go. Good girl.

24:48.760 --> 24:52.487
Come on. It's okay.

24:53.800 --> 24:55.180
Here she comes.

24:55.280 --> 24:57.260
Come on. Good girl.

24:57.360 --> 24:59.500
Good girl. Yeah.

24:59.600 --> 25:01.211
Come on.

25:01.680 --> 25:03.405
Attagirl.

25:05.480 --> 25:08.763
Good girl. We gotta get you
out of the pool, all right?

25:10.200 --> 25:11.765
Gotta make another cast.

25:12.800 --> 25:14.140
You keep getting bigger...

25:14.240 --> 25:17.649
so we gotta make a new tail.
So you can wear it.

25:17.960 --> 25:19.605
[CLICKS]

25:19.800 --> 25:21.047
When you feel better.

25:23.800 --> 25:25.300
She okay?

25:25.400 --> 25:26.840
I think so.

25:27.240 --> 25:29.940
CLAY: Okay, here we go.
Ready, Hazel? Phoebe?

25:30.040 --> 25:31.940
Good girl. Good girl.

25:32.040 --> 25:33.980
- It's coming to you, now.
- Okay.

25:34.080 --> 25:36.760
- Got it?
- Got it.

25:37.920 --> 25:39.610
SAWYER: It's okay.

25:40.680 --> 25:43.042
All right, let me know, Sawyer.

25:44.000 --> 25:45.220
SAWYER: Let's go.

25:45.320 --> 25:47.682
CLAY: All right, gang. Coming down.

25:52.320 --> 25:53.460
[WINTER SQUEALS]

25:53.560 --> 25:55.740
Hey! Easy, easy. It's okay.

25:55.840 --> 25:57.724
How's she looking?

26:07.280 --> 26:09.340
- Good?
- SAWYER: You're doing good.

26:09.440 --> 26:10.846
CLAY: Still good?

26:15.000 --> 26:16.486
Come on, it's okay.

26:18.120 --> 26:19.260
It's fine.

26:19.360 --> 26:20.660
[WINTER SQUEALING]

26:20.760 --> 26:24.089
Shh-shh-shh. It's okay.
You're doing good.

26:29.520 --> 26:30.767
[WINTER SQUEALS]

26:31.240 --> 26:33.220
- Oh, my gosh, Sawyer!
- PHOEBE: Winter!

26:33.320 --> 26:35.522
[WINTER SQUEALING AND SAWYER GASPING]

26:35.760 --> 26:38.122
- CLAY: Get him out of there!
- HAZEL: Sawyer!

26:41.400 --> 26:43.090
Sawyer! Get over here!

26:52.040 --> 26:54.607
I've got you.

26:55.640 --> 26:57.171
Come here!

27:00.520 --> 27:01.767
Are you okay?

27:02.480 --> 27:05.365
- I'm fine.
- Take a deep breath.

27:08.400 --> 27:11.285
[SAWYER PANTING]

27:11.920 --> 27:13.406
You're all right.

27:32.520 --> 27:35.940
<i>MAN [ON COMPUTER]: In very simple terms,
I think our mission here at SEA is to...</i>

27:36.040 --> 27:38.891
<i>prepare students to
learn on their own.</i>

27:51.360 --> 27:53.860
[MAN SPEAKING
INDISTINCTLY ON COMPUTER]

27:53.960 --> 27:55.844
Hey, hon.

27:56.120 --> 27:59.688
I scooped it for you. I thought
that might make it a little easier.

27:59.960 --> 28:01.730
Maybe later.

28:02.800 --> 28:05.401
Mom. Stop.

28:08.480 --> 28:10.569
I'm so sorry, honey.

28:12.800 --> 28:15.321
Any idea why Winter
might have done it?

28:16.480 --> 28:18.060
I don't.

28:18.160 --> 28:21.740
She didn't mean to.
She just got freaked out.

28:21.840 --> 28:24.122
She's a wild animal.

28:26.480 --> 28:29.524
Dr. Clay said anything about
when you can go back in?

28:30.920 --> 28:32.451
Nope.

28:39.800 --> 28:42.820
I hate to nag, honey, but Dr.
Arroyo needs an answer soon...

28:42.920 --> 28:44.246
Mom, I know, okay?

28:45.000 --> 28:47.487
When I have an answer, I'll say so.

28:53.520 --> 28:55.051
Come on.

28:55.400 --> 28:57.011
Stupid...

28:59.000 --> 29:00.565
[DOOR OPENS]

29:01.160 --> 29:03.300
- Hey, Clay.
- George.

29:03.400 --> 29:06.420
Hope I didn't startle you.
Couple of your staff let me in.

29:06.520 --> 29:08.722
The place has
really grown, hasn't it?

29:09.080 --> 29:12.011
Hey, Clay? We need to...

29:12.120 --> 29:13.460
Oh.

29:13.560 --> 29:16.923
- Phoebe, I think we might be a while.
- Right.

29:18.120 --> 29:22.460
I was really sorry to hear about
your bottlenose, CMA 0219.

29:22.560 --> 29:23.940
Yeah, Panama.

29:24.040 --> 29:26.460
Yeah. Anything in from the necropsy?

29:26.560 --> 29:30.020
Well, uh, she was confirmed
at over 40 years old.

29:30.120 --> 29:32.660
Pathology points to
respiratory failure.

29:32.760 --> 29:35.100
That's common at that age.

29:35.200 --> 29:37.580
Tell you what though.
She lived a good, long life.

29:37.680 --> 29:40.121
Yeah. She did.

29:41.080 --> 29:44.682
And what about
her companion, CMA 1108?

29:45.320 --> 29:49.923
Winter. Right.
She's, uh, right over there.

29:50.080 --> 29:51.486
GEORGE: Hmm.

29:52.600 --> 29:55.820
Hey, Clay?
Paint's kind of peeling here.

29:55.920 --> 29:58.780
You watch that. You don't want
that falling into the pool.

29:58.880 --> 30:00.445
Yeah.

30:05.080 --> 30:06.805
GEORGE: Behavior's certainly off.

30:09.360 --> 30:13.540
I see the blood work shows
elevated cortisol levels.

30:13.640 --> 30:15.808
Clay, this animal is
severely stressed.

30:16.000 --> 30:21.411
Yeah. We're doing routine medical
work-ups, keeping a 24 hour watch.

30:22.680 --> 30:26.060
It's a major violation for her to be
isolated like this. You know that.

30:26.160 --> 30:27.340
I know.

30:27.440 --> 30:31.140
It's temporary though.
We have Mandy. 1307A?

30:31.240 --> 30:33.580
- Oh, yeah.
- She's rehabbing great.

30:33.680 --> 30:36.820
And, uh, hoping to get them
paired up as soon as possible.

30:36.920 --> 30:39.248
When do you think that will be?

30:40.040 --> 30:41.605
Don't know.

30:42.120 --> 30:43.367
I see.

30:44.120 --> 30:46.448
[CLICKING]

30:51.320 --> 30:53.180
Clay?

30:53.280 --> 30:56.927
- I'm gonna be perfectly frank with you.
- CLAY: Please do.

30:57.200 --> 30:59.846
I'm gonna write you up
for a number of violations.

30:59.960 --> 31:01.844
All right.

31:03.840 --> 31:06.180
Back-up generator has not
been tested in 6 months.

31:06.280 --> 31:09.140
Fish freezer, the temperature's
a couple degrees too high.

31:09.240 --> 31:10.380
Okay.

31:10.480 --> 31:12.980
And look after the paint
around the pool, will you?

31:13.080 --> 31:14.940
Yeah, sure.

31:15.040 --> 31:21.521
However, the most egregious violation
is your female bottlenose, Winter.

31:23.680 --> 31:25.340
She's not doing well, Clay.

31:25.440 --> 31:29.060
She's stressed, she's isolated,
her scoliosis is getting worse.

31:29.160 --> 31:32.580
That animal needs to be paired
with another female, and soon.

31:32.680 --> 31:34.803
Okay, I know you know that.

31:35.560 --> 31:38.411
But it's my job to make
it official, right?

31:39.480 --> 31:42.445
I'm giving you 30 days
to correct the problem.

31:46.680 --> 31:48.689
Thanks for the root beer.

31:52.200 --> 31:53.970
Hello.

32:01.560 --> 32:04.604
What do you think?
Ready for a field trip?

32:21.880 --> 32:23.844
Mavis Haskett?

32:33.800 --> 32:36.140
I hear you're getting your own MRI.

32:36.240 --> 32:39.580
- Yeah!
- Well, that's exciting, but I'll miss your visits.

32:39.680 --> 32:41.120
[RUFUS GRUNTS]

32:45.000 --> 32:46.247
Okay, Mavis!

32:47.400 --> 32:48.540
[GRUNTS]

32:48.640 --> 32:50.524
Say "cheese."

32:57.360 --> 33:00.380
<i>WOMAN [OVER PA]: Ladies and gentlemen,
we have an otter presentation...</i>

33:00.480 --> 33:03.420
<i>starting in five minutes
by the upstairs pool.</i>

33:03.520 --> 33:05.500
<i>That's five minutes.</i>

33:05.600 --> 33:08.201
Um, Sawyer?

33:09.600 --> 33:11.245
Hey.

33:13.320 --> 33:16.922
Sorry to bother you,
but that's my grandpa.

33:17.160 --> 33:21.020
He's just visiting, and I know no one's
supposed to get close to Winter...

33:21.120 --> 33:25.180
but I was wondering if there's any
chance he could just have a peek?

33:25.280 --> 33:27.180
Now, Suze, don't strong-arm the man.

33:27.280 --> 33:29.323
I'm not. I'm just asking.

33:29.800 --> 33:31.889
If not, we totally understand.

33:35.920 --> 33:39.090
I've got an idea. Here, follow me.

33:42.600 --> 33:44.620
I'm okay. I'm okay.

33:44.720 --> 33:48.003
I've been walking on this thing
since before your mom was born.

33:49.200 --> 33:51.528
- Over here, guys.
- I'm okay.

33:52.040 --> 33:53.685
Can you help me with this?

33:54.840 --> 33:58.044
- What happened to your hand?
- Oh. I fell.

34:06.120 --> 34:08.049
See, she's just right over here.

34:09.639 --> 34:13.242
Well, would you look at that!

34:15.000 --> 34:17.328
Man, there's nothing there.

34:18.480 --> 34:20.967
How come she's not wearing her rig?

34:21.600 --> 34:25.407
She's been kind of down lately.
Hasn't really felt like it.

34:29.440 --> 34:31.324
Yeah, we all get that.

34:32.960 --> 34:34.206
Hmm.

34:36.880 --> 34:38.809
This is very cool.

34:41.960 --> 34:44.003
It's very cool.

34:50.080 --> 34:51.804
Hey.

34:53.520 --> 34:54.766
[WINTER CLICKING]

35:04.720 --> 35:08.811
Her eyes have really cleared up.
Her sunburn's looking a lot better too.

35:11.680 --> 35:13.689
That's a healthy-looking animal.

35:17.680 --> 35:19.609
She sure is.

35:20.080 --> 35:23.489
Okay, guys, I have
Mandy's test results here.

35:24.040 --> 35:27.580
I wanted to talk to you two about them
first before I briefed anybody else.

35:27.680 --> 35:29.166
Okay.

35:30.000 --> 35:31.690
CLAY: So...

35:32.040 --> 35:34.020
her blood work is all fine.

35:34.120 --> 35:36.243
Her gastrics are all fine.

35:37.360 --> 35:40.380
X-rays of her lungs, all negative.

35:40.480 --> 35:42.523
That's a good thing.

35:42.680 --> 35:45.700
There's no sign of infection,
so we've discontinued antibiotics.

35:45.800 --> 35:47.729
White cell count is normal.

35:48.800 --> 35:51.651
And her sunburn is totally healed.

35:52.520 --> 35:54.620
That is pretty much
a clean bill of health.

35:54.720 --> 35:55.980
- Yeah.
- That's fantastic.

35:56.080 --> 35:59.460
So can we talk about pairing her
with Winter because after Winter...

35:59.560 --> 36:00.841
Hazel.

36:01.320 --> 36:03.727
What I'm saying is that Mandy's fine.

36:08.120 --> 36:10.049
Do you hear what I'm saying?

36:11.480 --> 36:14.860
Mandy's really fine. And we have
an obligation to let every animal...

36:14.960 --> 36:17.980
- You can't release her.
- How can I not release her?

36:18.080 --> 36:21.340
All you have to do is wait six months or
a year until we find another female...

36:21.440 --> 36:23.900
Six months or 10 years!
We don't know what's gonna happen.

36:24.000 --> 36:27.380
If Mandy can go home,
then she deserves to go home.

36:27.480 --> 36:28.940
But we'll lose Winter!

36:29.040 --> 36:31.380
We lost Panama.
Now we're gonna lose Mandy!

36:31.480 --> 36:34.380
Hazel! I get it!
This is not all about Winter!

36:34.480 --> 36:37.380
If Mandy can catch live fish,
and that is the last test...

36:37.480 --> 36:41.287
then that's a decision
that I will have to make!

36:41.520 --> 36:43.529
- All right?
- Ugh.

37:11.440 --> 37:12.940
Hey.

37:13.040 --> 37:15.846
Hey. How's Hazel?

37:17.040 --> 37:18.651
She's gone to bed.

37:20.960 --> 37:25.165
I am not exactly her
favorite person right now.

37:28.040 --> 37:29.924
Well, what you gonna do?

37:31.800 --> 37:35.482
Speaking of which,
what are you gonna do?

37:36.360 --> 37:38.244
Oh, I don't know.

37:41.320 --> 37:44.820
Something tells me you have some fatherly
advice all lined up, though. Heh.

37:44.920 --> 37:46.940
Oh, I've always got that.

37:47.040 --> 37:49.780
In this case, I only got three words.

37:49.880 --> 37:51.764
And they're not mine, they're yours.

37:52.440 --> 37:53.580
Mine?

37:53.680 --> 37:57.009
All the way back when
you started this place...

37:57.200 --> 38:01.371
you wrote three words on the back
of a cocktail napkin at Frenchy's.

38:01.480 --> 38:03.045
[CHUCKLES]

38:05.120 --> 38:09.564
"Rescue. Rehab. Release."

38:10.000 --> 38:11.611
[CHUCKLES]

38:11.800 --> 38:14.048
The words you built this place on.

38:15.080 --> 38:19.524
You didn't build it to keep animals.
You built it to heal them and let them go.

38:21.080 --> 38:22.580
Tell me something.

38:22.680 --> 38:25.645
Poor Winter can't ever go home.

38:26.520 --> 38:28.290
But if she could...

38:31.440 --> 38:34.689
- In a heartbeat.
- There you go.

38:38.280 --> 38:39.860
[GROANS]

38:39.960 --> 38:41.730
How am I gonna tell Hazel?

38:42.160 --> 38:43.860
Beats me.

38:43.960 --> 38:47.140
I got enough trouble trying to
figure out how to talk to you.

38:47.240 --> 38:49.647
[CHUCKLES]

38:52.000 --> 38:54.123
I find myself out of thread here.

39:13.560 --> 39:15.100
What you doing?

39:15.200 --> 39:16.970
Going for a run.

39:19.440 --> 39:21.260
I was thinking maybe we should talk.

39:21.360 --> 39:23.820
No, you're thinking you should talk.

39:23.920 --> 39:25.531
I should listen.

39:26.200 --> 39:29.563
- Come on, Hazel.
- I told you, I'm going for a run.

39:32.280 --> 39:34.164
Hazel!

39:35.200 --> 39:37.004
[CLAY SIGHS]

39:39.520 --> 39:43.180
HAZEL: It's like I'm a plate-glass window.
He doesn't even see me.

39:43.280 --> 39:45.580
Your dad does have a lot
on his mind right now.

39:45.680 --> 39:48.420
Yeah, but he doesn't listen to me,
he doesn't tell me things.

39:48.520 --> 39:51.180
All I'm saying is keep
Mandy a few months...

39:51.280 --> 39:55.380
just till Winter's settled and we can pair
her with another female. But he won't try.

39:55.480 --> 39:57.700
It's like he doesn't care
about Winter anymore.

39:57.800 --> 40:00.321
Hazel, you know that's not true.

40:03.560 --> 40:06.260
I'm sorry for just
dumping all this on you.

40:06.360 --> 40:07.980
[SIREN WAILING NEARBY]

40:08.080 --> 40:10.248
I just didn't know
who else to talk to.

40:10.960 --> 40:13.242
Well, I don't know
much about dolphins.

40:14.280 --> 40:16.721
I know about hospitals though.

40:17.440 --> 40:20.484
- You know what I sometimes think?
- What?

40:21.560 --> 40:24.140
What if someday I came to
work and the place was empty?

40:24.240 --> 40:26.780
Just room after room, no patients.

40:26.880 --> 40:31.420
Bunch of bored doctors and nurses sitting
around because everybody was fine.

40:31.520 --> 40:33.961
No need for surgery. No sick people.

40:35.560 --> 40:37.340
No one's here because
they want to be.

40:37.440 --> 40:39.847
They're here because they need to be.

40:40.040 --> 40:43.323
And I assure you, no one stays one
minute longer than they have to.

40:45.520 --> 40:47.449
Talk to your dad.

40:47.960 --> 40:51.607
You kids take us by surprise.
You grow up so stinking fast.

40:53.400 --> 40:58.367
Talk to him the way you want him to
talk to you. Do something grown-up.

40:59.400 --> 41:01.364
Take him out for coffee.

41:02.840 --> 41:05.725
I hate coffee. This is hot chocolate.

41:06.560 --> 41:08.762
[LORRAINE CHUCKLES]

41:19.160 --> 41:21.900
I was born the year you and
mom started the aquarium...

41:22.000 --> 41:24.601
so technically I've been
here as long as you have.

41:25.760 --> 41:27.291
Yeah.

41:27.800 --> 41:29.570
That's true.

41:30.480 --> 41:34.220
Then it's not right to exclude me
from things, because I'm not a child.

41:34.320 --> 41:38.286
I'm as capable of making informed
decisions as anyone here.

41:41.080 --> 41:42.805
Yeah.

41:43.400 --> 41:46.180
- You are.
- So if we are going to consider Mandy...

41:46.280 --> 41:47.780
a candidate for release...

41:47.880 --> 41:52.380
I'd like to see her files: medical
records, blood works, cytologies.

41:52.480 --> 41:54.444
I'd like to read them now, please.

41:56.320 --> 41:58.682
Yeah. Okay.

42:00.000 --> 42:01.850
Have at it.

42:02.920 --> 42:04.929
Could you hand them to me?

42:06.960 --> 42:09.288
Yeah. Um...

42:09.560 --> 42:11.205
Okay.

42:15.640 --> 42:16.966
Thank you.

42:18.160 --> 42:20.044
You got it.

42:28.000 --> 42:29.725
[SIGHS]

42:33.960 --> 42:35.730
Hmm.

42:40.520 --> 42:42.165
[SIGHS]

43:11.680 --> 43:13.900
- CLAY: How's she doing, Kat?
- KAT: I think we're good.

43:14.000 --> 43:15.180
CLAY: Okay.

43:15.280 --> 43:17.721
All right, Sawyer, get the gate.

43:19.880 --> 43:21.220
HAZEL: Hey. Is that them?

43:21.320 --> 43:22.940
Yeah. Half-dozen.

43:23.040 --> 43:25.129
Okay. That should be fine.

43:26.720 --> 43:28.126
Okay.

43:32.920 --> 43:35.168
CLAY: Okay, everyone,
don't stand too close.

43:40.520 --> 43:42.609
- Everybody ready?
- Yup.

43:47.920 --> 43:49.884
[CLICKING]

44:07.600 --> 44:09.460
HORDERN: Of course you have a choice.

44:09.560 --> 44:12.740
- I have an obligation to every...
- Your obligation is to this institution...

44:12.840 --> 44:16.580
and the people and the animals and the
work we've done over the last three years.

44:16.680 --> 44:19.180
Think about the community!
What Winter means to them!

44:19.280 --> 44:20.860
I have a job to do, Phil.

44:20.960 --> 44:24.940
If you let Mandy go, the government will
take Winter, and that is it, end of story.

44:25.040 --> 44:27.740
I can't morally keep
her in captivity!

44:27.840 --> 44:29.644
- So we lose Winter?
- We might.

44:32.320 --> 44:36.980
When we shook hands on the dock that day
you told me I could run this place my way!

44:37.080 --> 44:39.203
And that's what I'm doing!

44:40.360 --> 44:43.086
If you don't like it, fire me.

44:46.480 --> 44:48.860
All right, guys. Keep tension
on the ropes, please.

44:48.960 --> 44:51.686
Are you guys ready down there?
Here we go.

44:52.400 --> 44:55.420
PHOEBE: As soon as she gets past
the ledge, Skip, turn her to your side.

44:55.520 --> 44:59.611
- We're gonna take her in tail first, all right?
- Keep the rope tight, please.

45:02.840 --> 45:04.180
Nice work.

45:04.280 --> 45:06.721
Easy, easy. Cammy, Maxie,
please go on that side.

45:07.960 --> 45:09.207
Easy.

45:09.600 --> 45:11.300
WOMAN 1:
Take your time. Watch her fluke.

45:11.400 --> 45:12.580
WOMAN 2: Hold it steady.

45:12.680 --> 45:15.340
I figure you've been on
enough of these releases.

45:15.440 --> 45:17.642
Why don't you take over from here?

45:19.040 --> 45:20.900
Are you serious?

45:21.000 --> 45:23.885
Yeah. You could do
this in your sleep.

45:26.600 --> 45:28.180
Just don't.

45:28.280 --> 45:31.563
Clay? She's leaning a little.
Is that okay?

45:36.120 --> 45:38.500
Yeah! Yeah, that's fine, Kat!

45:38.600 --> 45:40.740
Just watch her pec on
that far side. Tuck it.

45:40.840 --> 45:42.451
KAT: Okay, got it!

45:42.920 --> 45:44.060
Nice job.

45:44.160 --> 45:46.647
PHOEBE: Lower her to my side
as we go up the ramp. Ready?

46:01.440 --> 46:02.860
All right. Here we go, guys.

46:02.960 --> 46:04.140
GIRL 1: What is it?

46:04.240 --> 46:06.700
- GIRL 2: I just wanted to watch it.
- GIRL 1: Oh, yeah, me too.

46:06.800 --> 46:08.570
WOMAN 1: So exciting.

46:12.080 --> 46:14.980
Radio check? Kyle, do you read me?

46:15.080 --> 46:16.486
Kyle?

46:17.720 --> 46:19.340
Yeah, I hear you.

46:19.440 --> 46:22.769
Sorry, but who is this?
Is that you, Phoebe?

46:23.080 --> 46:24.611
It's Hazel.

46:26.600 --> 46:28.900
It's Hazel. Heh, heh.

46:29.000 --> 46:32.180
Hey, Hazel. I'm reading
you loud and clear.

46:32.280 --> 46:36.201
Hazel! Look! It's Mandy.

46:41.080 --> 46:43.886
PHOEBE: Ready? One, two, three!

46:45.680 --> 46:47.723
- Go slow, slow, slow.
- WOMAN 2: Keep it level.

46:48.800 --> 46:51.321
[MANDY CLICKING]

46:52.960 --> 46:54.650
CLAY: Go slow, go slow.

46:58.520 --> 47:01.007
- HAZEL: Dad, lower yours a little bit.
- Okay.

47:05.920 --> 47:08.009
HAZEL: Phoebe, watch your pole.

47:10.720 --> 47:13.241
PHOEBE: We're doing good, guys.
Just watch your footings.

47:13.400 --> 47:15.045
Breath.

47:15.680 --> 47:17.120
Nice and steady.

47:17.240 --> 47:18.965
Good work, guys.

47:24.240 --> 47:26.681
Okay. That's good. Stop here.

47:28.960 --> 47:30.924
How's she doing?

47:31.360 --> 47:32.500
[MANDY CLICKS]

47:32.600 --> 47:34.165
Looks like she's ready to go.

47:34.480 --> 47:35.841
How's the transmitter?

47:36.920 --> 47:38.420
All good.

47:38.520 --> 47:40.563
We're good here, Kyle.
You got a signal?

47:44.160 --> 47:46.362
You bet. Signal's nice and strong.

47:46.680 --> 47:48.060
HAZEL: Okay.

47:48.160 --> 47:52.180
All right, everyone, right side. We're
gonna lower our poles on three. Ready?

47:52.280 --> 47:54.403
One, two, three!

47:55.000 --> 47:56.486
[CLICKING]

47:59.560 --> 48:01.220
- Got her?
- Yeah.

48:01.320 --> 48:04.683
All right, left side, on three.
Ready? One, two, three!

48:07.560 --> 48:09.171
Good.

48:13.480 --> 48:15.330
[HAZEL LAUGHS]

48:17.800 --> 48:19.445
Go on.

48:20.360 --> 48:22.767
- Go on, Mandy.
- Go, Mandy.

48:24.680 --> 48:26.530
GIRL: Go, Mandy!

48:27.880 --> 48:30.401
[ALL CHEERING]

48:34.320 --> 48:36.682
Yes! Whoo!

48:37.200 --> 48:39.289
There we go! Go, Mandy!

48:42.760 --> 48:44.962
Look at that.
She's starting to take off.

48:48.360 --> 48:51.660
Bye, Mandy! Get home safe!

48:51.760 --> 48:54.122
Wow. She is really moving fast!

48:54.640 --> 48:57.810
- Yeah.
- Hang on. Something's coming.

49:00.440 --> 49:03.166
- What do you see?
- I don't know.

49:03.880 --> 49:06.180
What do you see, Kyle?

49:06.280 --> 49:08.448
It's a school of something.

49:08.640 --> 49:11.420
Sharks maybe.
They're coming at her fast.

49:11.520 --> 49:13.768
- SAWYER: They should move in.
- No, wait.

49:14.600 --> 49:16.211
Dad.

49:16.480 --> 49:18.250
Look there!

49:20.680 --> 49:22.020
- Dolphins.
- HAZEL: Yeah.

49:22.120 --> 49:23.685
A whole pod.

49:28.760 --> 49:30.564
Kyle, they're bottlenose.

49:30.840 --> 49:32.660
- Are you sure?
- Yeah.

49:32.760 --> 49:34.610
Look, there they are!

49:40.760 --> 49:42.060
WOMAN: Look!

49:42.160 --> 49:44.010
Everybody, look! They're dolphins!

49:45.040 --> 49:47.129
[WHISTLING AND CHEERING]

49:49.720 --> 49:51.001
[CLICKING]

49:56.160 --> 49:59.443
[SQUEAKING AND CLICKING]

50:04.360 --> 50:06.483
Looks like they're giving
her a hero's welcome.

50:06.640 --> 50:08.340
Yeah, Mandy!

50:08.440 --> 50:10.404
[PEOPLE CLAPPING]

50:31.320 --> 50:33.329
HAZEL:
That was nice of you the other day.

50:34.160 --> 50:37.762
- SAWYER: What was?
- That veteran. Letting him see Winter.

50:38.040 --> 50:39.526
Thanks.

50:40.320 --> 50:42.204
And that volunteer too.

50:43.920 --> 50:46.020
- What's her name again?
- Who?

50:46.120 --> 50:47.500
The volunteer.

50:47.600 --> 50:50.121
Dark hair, this long.

50:50.520 --> 50:52.020
Oh.

50:52.120 --> 50:53.685
Susie.

51:01.880 --> 51:04.060
So you book your
flight to Boston yet?

51:04.160 --> 51:06.940
No. Well, Kyle did, but...

51:07.040 --> 51:09.641
- I don't know...
- What don't you know?

51:12.440 --> 51:16.008
I don't know if I'm gonna go.

51:16.200 --> 51:18.780
What? No, Sawyer, you have to!

51:18.880 --> 51:21.260
Why? Why do I have to?

51:21.360 --> 51:24.260
- Because it's such a great opportunity...
- I know it is!

51:24.360 --> 51:26.340
That's all anyone ever
says to me anymore!

51:26.440 --> 51:28.802
- I'm just happy for you!
- I get it!

51:29.720 --> 51:31.331
Sorry.

51:31.560 --> 51:34.650
Hazel, what am I supposed to do?

51:35.240 --> 51:38.180
Mandy's gone, Panama's gone,
Winter's getting worse.

51:38.280 --> 51:40.926
I'm not even allowed to
swim with her any more.

51:42.760 --> 51:44.644
How could I leave now?

52:04.080 --> 52:06.580
- What are you doing?
- This has gone on long enough.

52:06.680 --> 52:08.980
You are gonna get in so much trouble!

52:09.080 --> 52:10.611
Well, at least we'll know.

52:14.000 --> 52:15.770
Come on, Winter.

52:24.640 --> 52:25.966
Here she comes.

52:34.760 --> 52:38.089
- If she gets aggressive, just get out.
- Yeah. No kidding.

52:45.840 --> 52:46.980
Talk to her.

52:47.080 --> 52:48.780
I've got it. I've known her
longer than you have.

52:48.880 --> 52:50.460
Yeah, like, 10 minutes.

52:50.560 --> 52:52.740
You know what I mean.
Don't be so pushy.

52:52.840 --> 52:55.691
Hey. Hey, girl.

53:02.000 --> 53:03.540
[CLICKING]

53:03.640 --> 53:05.365
Show her your wrist.

53:13.480 --> 53:14.841
Here.

53:15.400 --> 53:16.761
See it?

53:17.400 --> 53:18.840
It's okay.

53:20.120 --> 53:21.685
I'm okay.

53:25.160 --> 53:26.540
Good girl.

53:26.640 --> 53:27.887
[CHIRPING]

53:29.240 --> 53:30.851
Tweety-bird.

53:32.200 --> 53:33.481
Answer her.

53:34.120 --> 53:35.620
[WHISTLES]

53:35.720 --> 53:37.490
[WINTER WHISTLING]

53:40.520 --> 53:41.846
Everything okay now?

53:43.520 --> 53:44.846
We good?

53:45.200 --> 53:46.731
- [WINTER SQUEALING]
- [SAWYER GASPS]

53:49.400 --> 53:51.728
Get him, Winter! Come on!

54:55.200 --> 54:57.004
- It worked!
- Yes!

55:00.960 --> 55:02.685
Gotcha! Serves you right!

55:03.320 --> 55:05.170
[HAZEL LAUGHING]

55:06.560 --> 55:08.489
[BOTH LAUGHING]

55:09.280 --> 55:11.323
- Come on.
- Ha-ha-ha.

56:23.880 --> 56:25.060
Good girl.

56:25.160 --> 56:26.805
She's a good girl.

56:28.840 --> 56:31.247
She's okay. Yeah, she's fine.

56:52.360 --> 56:53.940
[HAZEL LAUGHING]

56:54.040 --> 56:56.846
Hey! What do you think you're doing?

56:57.160 --> 56:58.700
[WINTER WHISTLING]

56:58.800 --> 57:01.620
- It wasn't his fault, Dad. It was my decision.
- No, it wasn't.

57:01.720 --> 57:05.083
I don't care whose it was!
It was dangerous.

57:05.960 --> 57:09.380
These aren't pets.
They're wild animals.

57:09.480 --> 57:12.684
- I told you specifically...
- But you weren't here.

57:13.000 --> 57:15.487
I know Winter better than anyone.

57:15.840 --> 57:19.060
So we made our own decision.
And she's fine.

57:19.160 --> 57:24.287
So don't blame Hazel for anything.
If you're gonna blame someone, blame me.

57:28.240 --> 57:30.169
Oh, guys...

57:33.080 --> 57:35.203
It doesn't even matter.

57:43.520 --> 57:45.643
George Hatton came by today.

57:46.080 --> 57:47.361
Another violation?

58:00.920 --> 58:02.406
CLAY: That's a transfer order.

58:04.080 --> 58:07.966
They're moving Winter
to a marine park...

58:08.560 --> 58:09.966
in Texas.

58:15.520 --> 58:17.006
I, um...

58:19.960 --> 58:21.491
I'm so sorry.

58:37.680 --> 58:40.900
Hey, Mom. I'm really sorry I'm late.

58:41.000 --> 58:42.260
It's okay, honey.

58:42.360 --> 58:46.380
I just was seized by this strange craving
for the grouper they have next door.

58:46.480 --> 58:48.887
What do you say we
grab a bite to eat?

58:49.560 --> 58:51.091
Yeah. Okay.

58:55.560 --> 58:57.460
Good. Not too crowded.

58:57.560 --> 58:59.660
How can you tell? It's so dark.

58:59.760 --> 59:02.060
ALL: Surprise!

59:02.160 --> 59:04.700
[LORRAINE LAUGHING]

59:04.800 --> 59:07.048
[CHEERING]

59:16.600 --> 59:19.660
[DANCE MUSIC PLAYING OVER SPEAKERS]

59:19.760 --> 59:22.406
[CHATTERING AND LAUGHING]

59:25.880 --> 59:27.940
- Hey. Sawyer!
- Hey.

59:28.040 --> 59:30.900
Hey, Sawyer. Good to see you.
Congratulations, young man.

59:31.000 --> 59:32.820
Hey, there he is!

59:32.920 --> 59:35.460
Sawyer, man of the hour.
Come say hi to everybody.

59:35.560 --> 59:37.364
You must be so thrilled.

59:37.640 --> 59:40.020
- Yeah.
- When do you guys leave?

59:40.120 --> 59:42.820
The 23rd. We're on the
noon flight out of Tampa.

59:42.920 --> 59:46.567
I can't even imagine how
excited you must be right now.

59:48.400 --> 59:50.540
KYLE: Yeah? Huh? Right?

59:50.640 --> 59:52.444
[KYLE CHUCKLES]

59:52.760 --> 59:54.620
You must be so happy for him.

59:54.720 --> 59:55.967
I am.

59:56.200 --> 59:58.004
And such a nice turnout.

59:58.400 --> 01:00:00.841
Shows you how much
people love that boy.

01:00:01.560 --> 01:00:02.780
They do.

01:00:02.880 --> 01:00:04.780
Oh, Lorraine! Sweetie!

01:00:04.880 --> 01:00:06.060
[LORRAINE GASPS]

01:00:06.160 --> 01:00:08.420
- Oh! So sorry.
- Oh, that's okay.

01:00:08.520 --> 01:00:10.460
Goodness. Here, let me help you.

01:00:10.560 --> 01:00:11.820
- Wow.
- Heh.

01:00:11.920 --> 01:00:14.851
I want him to go. I do. I just...

01:00:16.560 --> 01:00:19.700
I just don't want him to go. Heh.

01:00:19.800 --> 01:00:21.047
It's okay.

01:00:22.840 --> 01:00:24.300
Hey, Reed.

01:00:24.400 --> 01:00:25.580
Doc, you made it.

01:00:25.680 --> 01:00:28.500
- Oh, yeah. Never pass up a free meal.
- Heh.

01:00:28.600 --> 01:00:30.290
Where is the guest of honor?

01:00:33.760 --> 01:00:35.450
[SIGHS]

01:00:42.440 --> 01:00:43.620
Hey.

01:00:43.720 --> 01:00:46.161
- Hey.
- Brought you something.

01:00:47.000 --> 01:00:49.100
- Going away present.
- Thanks.

01:00:49.200 --> 01:00:52.802
It's an old Chinese custom. Open it.

01:00:57.480 --> 01:00:59.250
SAWYER: Wow.

01:01:00.040 --> 01:01:01.571
It's beautiful.

01:01:01.840 --> 01:01:03.660
MCCARTHY: Belonged to my Uncle Willy.

01:01:03.760 --> 01:01:07.442
Been sitting in my garage
since the Nixon administration.

01:01:17.280 --> 01:01:18.970
Uh...

01:01:21.480 --> 01:01:23.260
Well, thank you.

01:01:23.360 --> 01:01:25.403
[MCCARTHY CHUCKLES]

01:01:25.720 --> 01:01:26.900
Hit it.

01:01:27.000 --> 01:01:29.328
- What?
- Hit it.

01:01:30.720 --> 01:01:32.100
[TICKING]

01:01:32.200 --> 01:01:34.050
SAWYER: There it goes.

01:01:35.720 --> 01:01:36.967
[STOPS TICKING]

01:01:37.720 --> 01:01:39.340
Uh...

01:01:39.440 --> 01:01:41.608
[TICKING THEN STOPS TICKING]

01:01:43.160 --> 01:01:44.771
You see the problem?

01:01:47.640 --> 01:01:49.729
I'm about to get a
lesson here, aren't I?

01:01:53.280 --> 01:01:55.403
The watch is beautiful...

01:01:55.520 --> 01:02:00.203
but my guess is it sat in that box
so long, that it just stopped.

01:02:01.800 --> 01:02:05.482
You have to shake it up now and
then to get it moving forward.

01:02:08.720 --> 01:02:10.206
Okay.

01:02:12.920 --> 01:02:14.884
It's a big world, Sawyer.

01:02:16.640 --> 01:02:20.367
Too many opportunities out there
to spend your life in a box.

01:02:22.640 --> 01:02:25.241
No matter how nice the box is.

01:02:36.800 --> 01:02:38.286
Thank you.

01:02:40.280 --> 01:02:41.845
MCCARTHY: My pleasure.

01:02:56.040 --> 01:02:58.527
[WINTER WHISTLING]

01:03:00.200 --> 01:03:02.084
CLAY: How you feeling, girl?

01:03:02.760 --> 01:03:04.291
Yeah.

01:03:06.320 --> 01:03:08.090
Me too.

01:03:10.320 --> 01:03:13.126
[CELL PHONE RINGING]

01:03:16.080 --> 01:03:18.260
It's Clay Haskett. Who's calling?

01:03:18.360 --> 01:03:20.860
What? When?

01:03:20.960 --> 01:03:24.084
Yes! Yes, yes! Absolutely!

01:03:24.520 --> 01:03:27.380
Excuse me, please.
Excuse me. Excuse me.

01:03:27.480 --> 01:03:30.740
Hey, guys. I just heard from Clay.
It's urgent. He needs us right now.

01:03:30.840 --> 01:03:32.780
- Hey. What's going on?
- Marine Fisheries called.

01:03:32.880 --> 01:03:35.060
They just picked up a stranding.
They're on their way.

01:03:35.160 --> 01:03:36.486
SAWYER: Gosh.

01:03:37.240 --> 01:03:39.020
- MAN 1: Let's go!
- MAN 2: Abby, get that stuff.

01:03:39.120 --> 01:03:42.085
- WOMAN 1: Somebody help me with these!
- WOMAN 2: Yeah, stand them up!

01:03:42.320 --> 01:03:45.220
- MAN 3: Get these tables in the back!
- MAN 4: We'll put her over here!

01:03:45.320 --> 01:03:46.726
WOMAN 3: Grab those chairs!

01:03:47.240 --> 01:03:49.204
MAN 5: Guys, I need three more...

01:03:54.200 --> 01:03:56.846
CLAY: Hurry up, people.
We don't have a lot of time.

01:03:57.520 --> 01:03:59.940
- How's it going over there?
- KYLE: Clay, what do you need?

01:04:00.040 --> 01:04:02.220
I need that water level
down to four feet max.

01:04:02.320 --> 01:04:03.540
KYLE: We're on it.

01:04:03.640 --> 01:04:07.526
I need a path cleared here, folks.
All of this stuff out of here, right away.

01:04:08.120 --> 01:04:10.340
Clay! I got him!

01:04:10.440 --> 01:04:12.780
Steve, what's your ETA?

01:04:12.880 --> 01:04:14.127
How long?

01:04:14.640 --> 01:04:15.921
Twenty minutes.

01:04:16.240 --> 01:04:18.841
What did you say?
It's a juvenile male?

01:04:21.160 --> 01:04:23.567
Clay? It's a female.

01:04:25.840 --> 01:04:27.610
[HAZEL SIGHS]

01:04:28.240 --> 01:04:30.340
Well, I certainly
wasn't expecting this.

01:04:30.440 --> 01:04:33.883
Me neither. I'd have
worn a nicer tie.

01:04:34.920 --> 01:04:36.340
CLAY: All right, everyone.

01:04:36.440 --> 01:04:39.900
When that truck arrives, you will
hear one voice, and it will be mine.

01:04:40.000 --> 01:04:42.180
Does everyone have their assignments?

01:04:42.280 --> 01:04:45.780
Okay. Gonna need a stretcher team.
Phoebe, I want you at the head with me.

01:04:45.880 --> 01:04:48.460
- Gonna need some strong backs.
- Here's one right here.

01:04:48.560 --> 01:04:51.650
CLAY: Great. Get on up here. Sawyer?

01:04:51.800 --> 01:04:53.490
I want you right beside me.

01:04:53.680 --> 01:04:55.020
- Yes, sir.
- CLAY: Okay.

01:04:55.120 --> 01:04:57.100
Gonna need a couple
other people as well.

01:04:57.200 --> 01:04:59.300
I hope this one isn't
missing any parts.

01:04:59.400 --> 01:05:02.570
I mean, if it's lost its head,
there's not much I can do.

01:05:02.760 --> 01:05:04.460
That's them!

01:05:04.560 --> 01:05:06.091
[SIREN WAILING]

01:05:13.040 --> 01:05:15.607
All right, everyone!
Let's get ready to go! Come on!

01:05:26.840 --> 01:05:28.260
Hey, guys.

01:05:28.360 --> 01:05:29.900
ALL: Aw.

01:05:30.000 --> 01:05:32.940
She's stiffening up. Might not make it.
Gotta get her in the water fast!

01:05:33.040 --> 01:05:34.260
Dad, she's so little.

01:05:34.360 --> 01:05:36.500
I'm gonna take her myself.
Phoebe, clear the way!

01:05:36.600 --> 01:05:39.020
PHOEBE: Get out of the way!
Everybody get out of the way!

01:05:39.120 --> 01:05:40.300
I've gotta see this.

01:05:40.400 --> 01:05:41.761
- Come on.
- PHOEBE: Guys, move!

01:05:43.480 --> 01:05:44.620
Clear the way!

01:05:44.720 --> 01:05:46.206
Everyone move!

01:05:47.920 --> 01:05:49.246
Clear!

01:05:50.800 --> 01:05:52.580
- CLAY: How we doing over here?
- SAWYER: Good.

01:05:52.680 --> 01:05:54.609
Yeah? Okay, let's get
her in the water.

01:05:55.000 --> 01:05:56.326
Slowly...

01:05:59.200 --> 01:06:00.340
That's perfect.

01:06:00.440 --> 01:06:02.820
All right. We're coming down with her.
Phoebe, ready? Kat?

01:06:02.920 --> 01:06:04.804
- PHOEBE: Yeah, ready.
- CLAY: All right, Dad.

01:06:09.400 --> 01:06:11.045
Let me know, guys.

01:06:20.280 --> 01:06:21.740
How we looking, Kyle? Good?

01:06:21.840 --> 01:06:23.485
KYLE: Yeah. It's all you.

01:06:23.920 --> 01:06:25.485
CLAY: Let me know.

01:06:27.200 --> 01:06:28.765
Almost.

01:06:29.440 --> 01:06:31.483
- All right, that's good.
- CLAY: Cut it!

01:06:34.120 --> 01:06:35.765
Nice and easy, Phoebe.

01:06:38.080 --> 01:06:39.611
PHOEBE: Keep them even.

01:06:40.640 --> 01:06:41.887
Okay.

01:06:43.000 --> 01:06:45.328
Nice and easy. Come here, sweetie.

01:06:45.720 --> 01:06:49.163
I gotcha. I gotcha.

01:06:50.840 --> 01:06:51.980
Dad, listen.

01:06:52.080 --> 01:06:53.645
[WHISTLING]

01:06:55.120 --> 01:06:57.891
- Look at that!
- Oh, my gosh.

01:06:58.640 --> 01:07:00.683
- LORRAINE: Aw.
- Ha-ha-ha.

01:07:03.520 --> 01:07:05.722
LORRAINE:
Oh, my gosh. She's precious.

01:07:06.000 --> 01:07:07.850
For crying out loud.

01:07:08.520 --> 01:07:12.441
I've pulled anchovies off of
pizzas that were bigger than that.

01:07:12.600 --> 01:07:14.460
Hey, everyone. Great hustle.

01:07:14.560 --> 01:07:19.209
Really good work. I'm so proud
of everyone. That's fantastic.

01:07:19.400 --> 01:07:21.648
Great job, guys. Really good.

01:07:21.960 --> 01:07:24.527
[SQUEALING]

01:07:26.920 --> 01:07:29.043
Now all we can do is hope.

01:07:30.320 --> 01:07:32.045
That's her name.

01:07:35.360 --> 01:07:36.971
What do you think?

01:07:37.760 --> 01:07:39.200
Yeah.

01:07:41.040 --> 01:07:42.605
Everyone...

01:07:44.240 --> 01:07:46.408
let's say hello to Hope!

01:07:47.160 --> 01:07:48.940
[ALL CLAPPING]

01:07:49.040 --> 01:07:50.401
Hello, Hope.

01:07:50.600 --> 01:07:54.441
- PHOEBE: Hi, Hope.
- Come here, little girl. Come here.

01:07:54.560 --> 01:07:55.807
Yeah.

01:07:56.160 --> 01:07:57.566
Look at little Hope.

01:08:00.880 --> 01:08:03.845
[WHISTLING]

01:08:13.480 --> 01:08:17.859
<i>MEL [ON TV]: Well, good morning, Tampa.
It's August 25th, the dog days of summer.</i>

01:08:17.960 --> 01:08:20.100
<i>- To start us off this morning...</i>
- Hurry up! It's on!

01:08:20.200 --> 01:08:23.260
<i>...it's been a very busy few weeks at
our own Clearwater Marine Aquarium...</i>

01:08:23.359 --> 01:08:24.540
<i>hasn't it, Jenny?</i>

01:08:24.640 --> 01:08:28.180
<i>That's right, Mel. It started three weeks
ago, when a little stranded dolphin...</i>

01:08:28.279 --> 01:08:32.460
<i>named Hope was rescued and brought to
CMA. But because she is too young...</i>

01:08:32.560 --> 01:08:35.060
<i>to have learned from her mom
how to survive in the wild...</i>

01:08:35.160 --> 01:08:36.859
<i>she'll never be able to be released.</i>

01:08:36.960 --> 01:08:40.460
Yeah. I understand, George,
but I'm gonna need some time.

01:08:40.560 --> 01:08:42.888
Can you give me an extension?

01:08:43.960 --> 01:08:47.060
Yes, of course.
I will put it in writing.

01:08:47.160 --> 01:08:49.300
<i>JENNY: She might be a Godsend
to CMA's most famous...</i>

01:08:49.399 --> 01:08:50.819
I will put it in writing right now.

01:08:50.920 --> 01:08:55.540
<i>...resident, Winter, who recently lost
her companion, Panama, to old age.</i>

01:08:55.640 --> 01:09:00.660
<i>She's been lonely ever since, so it's
hoped that Hope may provide the answer.</i>

01:09:00.760 --> 01:09:02.979
Oh. That's adorable!

01:09:03.080 --> 01:09:06.300
- It's her favorite thing! She loves it! Heh.
- Ha-ha-ha.

01:09:06.399 --> 01:09:08.328
That is so cute!

01:09:08.439 --> 01:09:10.580
But there is even
more going on at CMA.

01:09:10.680 --> 01:09:14.540
Just this morning they released a
green sea turtle back into the wild.

01:09:14.640 --> 01:09:17.060
Mavis was found wrapped
up in fishing line.

01:09:17.160 --> 01:09:19.740
But once her flippers healed,
she was good to go.

01:09:19.840 --> 01:09:22.180
Whoa! Look out! Wild bird!

01:09:22.279 --> 01:09:25.740
I know! This pelican
wanted in on the action.

01:09:25.840 --> 01:09:28.500
Boy, that is one feisty pelican!

01:09:28.600 --> 01:09:30.040
You're telling me?

01:09:30.560 --> 01:09:31.700
[RUFUS GRUNTS]

01:09:31.800 --> 01:09:34.367
Rufus! No! Go away! Stop it!

01:09:35.279 --> 01:09:37.540
- Go away!
- SAWYER: All right. Here's good.

01:09:37.640 --> 01:09:39.380
- Hazel, will you get him, please?
- I will.

01:09:39.479 --> 01:09:40.805
Okay, easy, easy.

01:09:40.960 --> 01:09:43.560
Okay. Whoa. Okay.

01:09:46.319 --> 01:09:47.850
I've got him! Just go!

01:09:48.479 --> 01:09:50.260
- No. Sorry.
- All right. Are we good?

01:09:50.359 --> 01:09:51.899
HAZEL: No! Don't do it!

01:09:52.000 --> 01:09:55.602
Okay, there you go.
Rufus, come on. No!

01:09:57.040 --> 01:09:58.220
I got him! Just go!

01:09:58.320 --> 01:09:59.740
- Mavis!
- Go, Mavis!

01:09:59.840 --> 01:10:01.340
[ALL CHEERING]

01:10:01.440 --> 01:10:02.580
Go, Mavis!

01:10:02.680 --> 01:10:04.291
Go, Mavis!

01:10:06.080 --> 01:10:08.931
HAZEL: No! Nope! Come on! Stay back!

01:10:09.280 --> 01:10:12.484
Shoo! No! No, you don't! No!

01:10:13.520 --> 01:10:14.960
Come on!

01:10:15.080 --> 01:10:16.805
Go, Mavis!

01:10:20.160 --> 01:10:21.646
Bye!

01:10:22.680 --> 01:10:24.928
- Wow, she's really going!
- WOMAN 1: Oh, yeah.

01:10:25.640 --> 01:10:27.365
WOMAN 2: Go, Mavis!

01:10:28.680 --> 01:10:30.006
HAZEL: No, no, no!

01:10:31.600 --> 01:10:34.451
Hey! Rufus!

01:10:34.640 --> 01:10:36.410
Rufus!

01:10:41.320 --> 01:10:42.726
Crazy bird.

01:10:47.200 --> 01:10:48.731
What's he doing?

01:10:51.400 --> 01:10:53.443
No! Rufus!

01:11:01.600 --> 01:11:04.220
Yes, Fire and Rescue. We're gonna
need everything fully equipped.

01:11:04.320 --> 01:11:06.860
EMT's, backboards, ambulances,
the whole nine yards.

01:11:06.960 --> 01:11:09.780
Is there any way we can get the same
guys we worked with in the past?

01:11:09.880 --> 01:11:11.740
Gastrics are good.
The animals are healthy.

01:11:11.840 --> 01:11:15.328
Of course we're ready, George.
8 a.m. Saturday.

01:11:16.600 --> 01:11:18.340
[KNOCK ON DOOR]

01:11:18.440 --> 01:11:19.971
Can I come in?

01:11:20.560 --> 01:11:22.171
Yeah.

01:11:28.360 --> 01:11:30.340
You know tomorrow's end of the month.

01:11:30.440 --> 01:11:33.803
Yeah, I know. Dr. Arroyo
needs an answer.

01:11:34.080 --> 01:11:38.604
- He does. And the longer you wait...
- Mom, I don't know.

01:11:39.280 --> 01:11:43.166
How can I tell him anything if I don't
know what's gonna happen with Winter?

01:11:44.480 --> 01:11:46.409
They can't hold your place forever.

01:11:48.280 --> 01:11:51.484
Honey, sometimes in life,
we just have to make a decision.

01:11:54.400 --> 01:11:56.682
Okay. I get it.

01:11:59.280 --> 01:12:01.050
Well, tomorrow is a big day.

01:12:01.720 --> 01:12:03.331
We'll see what happens.

01:12:11.800 --> 01:12:13.411
I love you.

01:12:14.080 --> 01:12:15.380
[CHUCKLES]

01:12:15.480 --> 01:12:18.206
I know. I love you too.

01:12:20.440 --> 01:12:22.847
- Off?
- Yeah. Thank you.

01:12:37.800 --> 01:12:40.526
[TICKING]

01:12:54.840 --> 01:12:57.520
[TICKING]

01:13:12.840 --> 01:13:16.100
PHOEBE: Remember, today needs
to feel just like a normal day.

01:13:16.200 --> 01:13:20.166
They'll have their sessions. Kat will
have Hope. Sawyer will have Winter.

01:13:20.360 --> 01:13:23.530
Everybody knows their assignments?
Gate minders?

01:13:23.920 --> 01:13:26.180
- Uh, Kyle, where are you?
- Back here.

01:13:26.280 --> 01:13:29.940
Kyle is our safety. If anybody
feels like they are in trouble...

01:13:30.040 --> 01:13:32.686
his word is law. Okay?

01:13:33.760 --> 01:13:35.325
Sawyer.

01:13:38.880 --> 01:13:40.020
Okay.

01:13:40.120 --> 01:13:43.060
First of all, I want to thank
everyone for their hard work...

01:13:43.160 --> 01:13:47.206
and preparation for this moment.
You guys are fantastic. Thank you. Yes.

01:13:51.360 --> 01:13:52.700
But remember...

01:13:52.800 --> 01:13:56.561
no matter how much we love Hope
and Winter, they are wild animals.

01:13:57.240 --> 01:14:02.048
They can bite or rake each other with
their teeth, and even draw blood.

01:14:02.600 --> 01:14:04.290
Or head-butt.

01:14:04.480 --> 01:14:06.700
Take a cheap shot when
the other one's not looking.

01:14:06.800 --> 01:14:09.571
That's how they establish
dominance in the wild.

01:14:09.760 --> 01:14:12.440
It's natural, but it can be rough.

01:14:12.760 --> 01:14:15.740
Reed, Rebecca, Jeanette,
you guys have the net, right?

01:14:15.840 --> 01:14:17.280
Yeah.

01:14:17.480 --> 01:14:18.940
If they go after each other...

01:14:19.040 --> 01:14:22.961
you divers look for Phoebe's signal
to get the net between them fast.

01:14:24.160 --> 01:14:28.649
But if it all goes well, and they
accept each other, you'll see this:

01:14:28.800 --> 01:14:33.500
Parallel swimming and easy,
natural, relaxed behavior.

01:14:33.600 --> 01:14:38.488
But anything else...
Anything that looks aggressive...

01:14:40.560 --> 01:14:44.526
safety first. Theirs and ours.

01:14:45.760 --> 01:14:48.380
All right. Uh, any questions?

01:14:48.480 --> 01:14:49.966
Yeah.

01:14:50.200 --> 01:14:51.660
Yeah. Dr. Clay.

01:14:51.760 --> 01:14:53.883
When did you get so bossy?

01:14:54.120 --> 01:14:55.560
[ALL LAUGH]

01:15:04.200 --> 01:15:05.925
You guys get the net.

01:15:06.680 --> 01:15:09.247
- Remember, stay calm.
- MAN: Got it.

01:15:12.160 --> 01:15:14.681
Let's move this. Put it in the back.

01:15:22.200 --> 01:15:25.006
- KYLE: All set here?
- REED: Yeah.

01:15:26.160 --> 01:15:28.806
[CHATTERING]

01:15:35.160 --> 01:15:37.408
- SAWYER: Unh.
- Sorry.

01:15:39.680 --> 01:15:41.100
Um...

01:15:41.200 --> 01:15:42.526
Good luck today.

01:15:44.360 --> 01:15:45.891
Thanks.

01:15:48.800 --> 01:15:50.047
- You ready?
- Yeah.

01:15:50.840 --> 01:15:53.500
Morning, morning, good morning.

01:15:53.600 --> 01:15:55.290
It's nice to meet you.

01:15:55.880 --> 01:15:58.020
- Reed. Kyle.
- Hey.

01:15:58.120 --> 01:15:59.860
- Morning, Mr. Hordern.
- Ready to do this?

01:15:59.960 --> 01:16:01.810
- Yes, sir.
- Hope it goes well.

01:16:01.960 --> 01:16:03.446
KYLE: Hope so.

01:16:05.520 --> 01:16:08.405
[SQUEALING]

01:16:09.560 --> 01:16:11.683
[CLICKING]

01:16:12.040 --> 01:16:14.925
Sawyer? Are you ready to go?

01:16:18.160 --> 01:16:19.540
You ready?

01:16:19.640 --> 01:16:21.285
All right.

01:16:24.040 --> 01:16:25.969
All right. Here we go.

01:16:27.000 --> 01:16:28.611
We got this.

01:16:32.040 --> 01:16:33.685
Is everybody set?

01:16:35.200 --> 01:16:36.540
We're good to go, Phoebe.

01:16:36.640 --> 01:16:38.649
Okay. Open the gate.

01:16:50.560 --> 01:16:52.569
[SQUEAKING]

01:16:52.840 --> 01:16:56.283
[WHISTLING]

01:17:12.840 --> 01:17:15.327
[WHISTLING]

01:17:22.760 --> 01:17:25.281
Okay, Kat. Go ahead and release Hope.

01:17:34.160 --> 01:17:36.362
[WHISTLING]

01:18:02.000 --> 01:18:04.407
[CLICKING]

01:18:18.240 --> 01:18:20.169
[HOPE SQUEALS]

01:18:41.640 --> 01:18:44.241
- Clay, I don't like this.
- Just give it a second.

01:18:49.400 --> 01:18:51.204
[SQUEALS]

01:18:53.640 --> 01:18:55.410
[CLICKING AND SQUEAKING]

01:19:02.200 --> 01:19:03.731
[SQUEAKS]

01:19:03.920 --> 01:19:05.060
Hang on.

01:19:05.160 --> 01:19:06.860
[SQUEAKING]

01:19:06.960 --> 01:19:09.083
- Hope!
- Hope!

01:19:12.280 --> 01:19:13.845
[SQUEAKING]

01:19:14.120 --> 01:19:15.446
Hope!

01:19:16.280 --> 01:19:19.086
- Get the net!
- No! Winter!

01:19:19.560 --> 01:19:21.569
PHOEBE: Wait, wait, wait! Hold up!

01:19:22.800 --> 01:19:24.081
[SQUEAKING]

01:19:27.240 --> 01:19:29.010
Close the gate!

01:19:30.400 --> 01:19:32.682
Oh, my gosh!
I hope they're all right.

01:19:43.760 --> 01:19:45.530
CLAY: Is everybody all right?

01:19:54.000 --> 01:19:56.580
- SAWYER: At first Winter was fine.
- HAZEL: Holding in the gate.

01:19:56.680 --> 01:19:58.220
PHOEBE: She's just being territorial.

01:19:58.320 --> 01:19:59.900
KYLE: She's saying, "it's my gate."

01:20:00.000 --> 01:20:01.611
There. Freeze it.

01:20:02.280 --> 01:20:04.340
- Look.
- She's echolocating.

01:20:04.440 --> 01:20:08.690
- Yeah, and she sees Winter has no tail.
- She doesn't like that. Here, then look.

01:20:09.720 --> 01:20:11.980
- See when Winter starts swimming?
- It freaked Hope out.

01:20:12.080 --> 01:20:13.380
Which then freaked Winter out.

01:20:13.480 --> 01:20:16.620
Because that movement's completely
unnatural. Hope doesn't understand that.

01:20:16.720 --> 01:20:18.700
Yeah, but there's nothing
we can do about that.

01:20:18.800 --> 01:20:20.684
That's the only way she can swim.

01:20:21.440 --> 01:20:22.721
Maybe not.

01:20:24.320 --> 01:20:25.851
What if she wore the tail?

01:20:26.280 --> 01:20:27.820
That would freak Hope out even more.

01:20:27.920 --> 01:20:30.060
But at least she'd have a
more natural swimming motion.

01:20:30.160 --> 01:20:31.820
She has never seen anything like it!

01:20:31.920 --> 01:20:33.180
It's just a huge contraption.

01:20:33.280 --> 01:20:34.900
KYLE:
But it's that up and down motion.

01:20:35.000 --> 01:20:37.140
Yeah, but if she smacks Hope
with it, it's game over.

01:20:37.240 --> 01:20:39.820
- KAT: Hope is so little.
- She hurt Sawyer. It's too dangerous.

01:20:39.920 --> 01:20:42.168
Hang on a second, guys. Sawyer...

01:20:42.920 --> 01:20:46.647
I want to know what you think.
She's been aggressive before, right?

01:20:47.120 --> 01:20:49.004
Think she'll do it again?

01:20:53.800 --> 01:20:55.260
No.

01:20:55.360 --> 01:20:58.291
No, that was my fault.

01:20:59.400 --> 01:21:02.444
I pushed her too fast,
she wasn't ready.

01:21:03.840 --> 01:21:07.123
And I know Winter.
And she's fine now.

01:21:07.520 --> 01:21:09.085
I can see it.

01:21:09.400 --> 01:21:12.604
I can see it in her eyes,
and the way she is with me.

01:21:13.680 --> 01:21:15.450
She's like how she always was.

01:21:16.360 --> 01:21:18.767
She never meant any harm.

01:21:21.360 --> 01:21:24.040
And if we don't give her
this chance, what do we do?

01:21:25.040 --> 01:21:26.480
Give up?

01:21:27.160 --> 01:21:30.284
I don't want to look back on
this knowing we didn't even try.

01:21:32.720 --> 01:21:34.206
Sawyer's right.

01:21:37.440 --> 01:21:38.687
Okay.

01:21:39.520 --> 01:21:42.929
Tomorrow, 8 a.m. With the tail.

01:21:44.600 --> 01:21:48.805
Anybody has a problem
with that, speak up now.

01:22:03.560 --> 01:22:06.460
- LORRAINE: Looks pretty busy.
- KYLE: Holy smoke!

01:22:06.560 --> 01:22:08.444
What on earth is the news doing here?

01:22:09.320 --> 01:22:10.540
I have no idea.

01:22:10.640 --> 01:22:12.860
Do you think they all
heard about the pairing?

01:22:12.960 --> 01:22:15.162
[CHATTERING]

01:22:16.560 --> 01:22:19.700
Sawyer! We heard you're trying to pair
Winter and Hope! Will you comment on it?

01:22:19.800 --> 01:22:21.980
You get inside.
I'll take care of this.

01:22:22.080 --> 01:22:24.660
- MAN 1: What about Winter?
- MAN 2: We heard they're moving Winter.

01:22:24.760 --> 01:22:27.220
REPORTER 1: We heard Winter's
moving to Texas. Is that true?

01:22:27.320 --> 01:22:30.649
Let him get to work. I know
you have a lot of questions...

01:22:31.440 --> 01:22:33.500
REPORTER 2: Kyle, can you
give us any information?

01:22:33.600 --> 01:22:35.220
KYLE:
When we have a statement ready...

01:22:35.320 --> 01:22:39.047
- BOY 1: Get your Hope and Winter T-shirt!
- GIRL 1: Can I get a T-shirt?

01:22:43.240 --> 01:22:44.521
GIRL 2: Hello, Sawyer!

01:22:45.720 --> 01:22:47.524
GIRL 3: Sawyer! Sawyer!

01:22:48.320 --> 01:22:51.729
PHOEBE: Okay, everybody,
remember this is just a normal day.

01:22:59.560 --> 01:23:01.091
Here we are.

01:23:01.280 --> 01:23:02.860
Cool. It's a whole new design.

01:23:02.960 --> 01:23:06.528
Yeah, more streamlined.
I finished it about 4:00 this morning.

01:23:06.960 --> 01:23:10.380
The joints are carbon fiber, and I
made the flukes a little darker...

01:23:10.480 --> 01:23:12.180
so it's easier to track movement.

01:23:12.280 --> 01:23:15.404
And I hope you'll notice
that they're a lot floppier.

01:23:15.680 --> 01:23:17.380
- More like the real thing?
- Yeah.

01:23:17.480 --> 01:23:19.020
How did you get these edges so soft?

01:23:19.120 --> 01:23:22.085
Three jars of meat tenderizer
and a baseball bat.

01:23:23.080 --> 01:23:24.500
Is this a new formula, too?

01:23:24.600 --> 01:23:30.250
No, kid. Same formula. I just made a
fresh one. Don't get greedy. All right.

01:23:30.960 --> 01:23:34.801
Yeah, they are. We're still here.
It's been about an hour.

01:23:35.320 --> 01:23:37.580
We haven't heard anything
in the aquarium for a while.

01:23:37.680 --> 01:23:41.009
It's been pretty
hush-hush around here.

01:23:49.720 --> 01:23:52.020
PHOEBE: Thanks. Sawyer,
you wanna show it to her?

01:23:52.120 --> 01:23:53.651
SAWYER: Yeah.

01:24:00.520 --> 01:24:02.051
She's okay.

01:24:03.720 --> 01:24:05.081
It's okay.

01:24:06.200 --> 01:24:07.890
But you gotta wear it now.

01:24:09.200 --> 01:24:11.243
It's the most important time ever.

01:24:11.680 --> 01:24:14.042
Dr. McCarthy made
it special, just for today.

01:24:14.680 --> 01:24:16.689
See? There he is.

01:24:17.520 --> 01:24:19.290
He stayed up all night
making it for you.

01:24:19.440 --> 01:24:21.540
[BLOWS AIR]

01:24:21.640 --> 01:24:23.180
My sentiments exactly.

01:24:23.280 --> 01:24:25.084
[SAWYER CHUCKLES]

01:24:26.200 --> 01:24:27.925
[SIGHS]

01:24:33.320 --> 01:24:35.780
Miss Hamilton. Phil Hordern.
It's an honor to have you here.

01:24:35.880 --> 01:24:37.445
Thank you for having me.

01:24:43.560 --> 01:24:44.841
[SQUEALING]

01:24:47.600 --> 01:24:49.020
PHOEBE: Clay?

01:24:49.120 --> 01:24:50.924
- It's on.
- Attagirl.

01:24:51.360 --> 01:24:52.540
All right, Kat, ready?

01:24:52.640 --> 01:24:54.080
Yep.

01:24:55.760 --> 01:24:57.086
Dad?

01:24:57.760 --> 01:25:00.247
- Ready.
- PHOEBE: Yeah. Let's go.

01:25:00.800 --> 01:25:03.002
All right. Let's get
her off the platform.

01:25:03.200 --> 01:25:07.803
All right. Up and down,
Winter. Come on.

01:25:09.800 --> 01:25:11.286
I think she likes it.

01:25:13.080 --> 01:25:14.520
Good girl.

01:25:14.960 --> 01:25:16.400
[WHISTLING]

01:25:18.680 --> 01:25:21.531
You hear that? That's Winter.

01:25:23.600 --> 01:25:25.820
Couple of chicks talking
trash over the fence.

01:25:25.920 --> 01:25:27.610
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

01:25:33.480 --> 01:25:36.650
All right. Anybody's not ready,
I want you to speak now.

01:25:37.560 --> 01:25:39.020
All right, Kat, Sawyer...

01:25:39.120 --> 01:25:42.563
be ready to pick them up
fast at my command, okay?

01:25:43.760 --> 01:25:45.724
I hope they like each other.

01:25:46.080 --> 01:25:47.645
Me too.

01:25:48.960 --> 01:25:51.925
All right. Open the gate.

01:26:01.440 --> 01:26:02.766
Here we go.

01:26:13.320 --> 01:26:15.329
[WHISTLING]

01:26:28.360 --> 01:26:30.528
[SQUEALING]

01:26:31.800 --> 01:26:34.401
Kat, send Hope.

01:26:35.600 --> 01:26:36.961
KAT: Go on.

01:26:44.000 --> 01:26:46.885
[CLICKING]

01:26:49.160 --> 01:26:51.010
Phew.

01:26:52.960 --> 01:26:56.004
[CLICKING]

01:27:04.400 --> 01:27:05.886
Stand-off.

01:27:06.080 --> 01:27:07.930
KYLE: Showdown at high noon.

01:27:10.800 --> 01:27:12.843
[SQUEALING]

01:27:21.360 --> 01:27:22.686
[CLICKING]

01:27:32.840 --> 01:27:34.769
[SQUEALING]

01:27:43.760 --> 01:27:45.644
- Clay?
- Hang on.

01:27:48.400 --> 01:27:49.806
Get ready with the net.

01:27:59.560 --> 01:28:01.205
Wait on the net! Wait!

01:28:12.520 --> 01:28:13.881
[CLICKING]

01:28:18.840 --> 01:28:20.087
[CLICKING]

01:28:30.800 --> 01:28:32.126
Let them go.

01:28:33.920 --> 01:28:36.771
[CLICKING]

01:28:37.600 --> 01:28:40.201
[SQUEALING]

01:28:53.160 --> 01:28:54.407
What are they doing?

01:28:55.800 --> 01:28:58.970
Nobody move. Nobody move!

01:29:12.120 --> 01:29:13.401
Here they come!

01:29:21.440 --> 01:29:22.766
They're accepting.

01:29:38.000 --> 01:29:39.281
They're accepting!

01:29:39.640 --> 01:29:41.285
[ALL CHEERING]

01:29:43.440 --> 01:29:44.880
Yes!

01:29:47.520 --> 01:29:50.929
[WHISTLING AND SQUEAKING]

01:29:52.360 --> 01:29:53.721
[LAUGHING]

01:29:57.880 --> 01:29:59.286
Well, I'll be darned.

01:29:59.400 --> 01:30:00.965
It's working! We did it!

01:30:02.120 --> 01:30:03.810
They did it! It Worked!

01:30:05.920 --> 01:30:07.645
Way to go!

01:30:08.240 --> 01:30:09.885
Whoo!

01:30:28.440 --> 01:30:30.020
I love that fish!

01:30:30.120 --> 01:30:31.460
Ah! She's not a fish!

01:30:31.560 --> 01:30:34.650
Ah, looks like a fish,
smells like a fish.

01:30:34.840 --> 01:30:36.087
[CHUCKLES]

01:30:39.240 --> 01:30:42.046
Way to go, Clay. You did it again.

01:30:43.760 --> 01:30:45.450
[HAZEL CHUCKLES]

01:30:46.840 --> 01:30:49.300
[WHISTLING]

01:30:49.400 --> 01:30:51.568
- Whoo!
- Look, Dad, they're playing!

01:30:56.840 --> 01:30:59.202
- Can I see that for a minute? Yep.
- Thanks.

01:30:59.560 --> 01:31:01.125
Whoa!

01:31:01.880 --> 01:31:03.969
[LAUGHING]

01:31:05.520 --> 01:31:06.660
Kyle...!

01:31:06.760 --> 01:31:08.405
[LAUGHS]

01:31:21.760 --> 01:31:23.962
[WHISTLING]

01:31:52.800 --> 01:31:54.331
I gotta go, Winter.

01:31:55.320 --> 01:31:56.851
Okay?

01:31:57.560 --> 01:31:59.000
I'll come back.

01:32:00.680 --> 01:32:02.370
I promise.

01:32:10.680 --> 01:32:14.282
<i>SAWYER: We don't know for sure if
dolphins feel emotion the way we do...</i>

01:32:14.520 --> 01:32:19.089
<i>fear, joy, sadness...</i>

01:32:20.200 --> 01:32:22.528
<i>but it feels like they do.</i>

01:32:25.640 --> 01:32:31.244
<i>They may even feel things
like loneliness, friendship, or loss.</i>

01:32:32.680 --> 01:32:34.450
<i>It's hard to say.</i>

01:32:37.480 --> 01:32:40.260
<i>I'd like to think that
instinctively they understand...</i>

01:32:40.360 --> 01:32:42.289
<i>that life has all of that in it.</i>

01:32:44.400 --> 01:32:45.965
<i>And that's not a bad thing.</i>

01:32:47.200 --> 01:32:49.323
<i>We just have to embrace it.</i>

01:32:59.200 --> 01:33:00.925
[CELL PHONE BEEPS]

01:33:06.360 --> 01:33:07.641
HAZEL: Sawyer!

01:33:08.280 --> 01:33:11.165
I'm on the roof! Up here!

01:33:11.480 --> 01:33:13.045
Whoo!

01:33:13.640 --> 01:33:16.241
- Hey, Mom. Can you pull over for a sec?
- LORRAINE: Mm-hm.

01:33:22.440 --> 01:33:24.085
Sawyer! Up here!

01:33:24.760 --> 01:33:27.201
- Sawyer!
- Is that Hazel?

01:33:28.520 --> 01:33:29.767
Yeah.

01:33:44.560 --> 01:33:46.364
[LAUGHS]

01:33:51.760 --> 01:33:53.580
Whoo! Aah!

01:33:53.680 --> 01:33:54.927
[HAZEL LAUGHS]

01:33:55.680 --> 01:33:57.041
[SAWYER CHUCKLES]

01:33:59.880 --> 01:34:01.650
Whoo!

01:34:04.680 --> 01:34:06.041
[LAUGHS]

01:34:14.600 --> 01:34:15.881
[CELL PHONE BEEPS]

01:34:29.160 --> 01:34:30.771
- LORRAINE: Oh!
- KYLE: What was that?

01:34:35.280 --> 01:34:37.130
[RUFUS GRUNTS]

01:34:39.280 --> 01:34:40.660
[GASPS]

01:34:40.760 --> 01:34:43.611
Rufus! You're back!

01:34:44.600 --> 01:34:46.404
Oh, Rufus.

01:34:47.280 --> 01:34:48.700
[GRUNTS]

01:34:48.800 --> 01:34:50.650
[CHUCKLES]

01:35:00.240 --> 01:35:01.851
[CELL PHONE BEEPS]

01:35:13.160 --> 01:35:17.251
<i>SAWYER: Because when one
door closes, another opens.</i>

01:35:18.400 --> 01:35:22.400
<i>Life is always full of possibilities.</i>

01:35:23.160 --> 01:35:24.646
Bye, Sawyer.

01:35:26.240 --> 01:35:28.010
Really gonna miss you.

01:36:24.560 --> 01:36:27.604
Lift your weight. Don't let the
other guy lift your weight.

01:36:39.960 --> 01:36:41.380
MAN 1: There we go.

01:36:41.480 --> 01:36:43.045
[ALL CHEERING]

01:36:53.320 --> 01:36:55.568
[CHATTERING]

01:36:56.920 --> 01:36:59.646
MAN 1: Get that stretcher
up here, that blue stretcher.

01:37:00.480 --> 01:37:02.205
MAN 2: I want her flipped around.

01:37:18.520 --> 01:37:20.927
Name is Hope.

01:37:21.240 --> 01:37:23.841
[PEOPLE CLAPPING]

